{{Infobox SCOTUS case |Litigants=Washington v. United States |ArgueDate=April 18 |ArgueYear=2018 |DecideDate=June 11 |DecideYear=2018 |FullName=Washington v. United States |Docket=17-269 |USVol=584 |USPage=___ |ParallelCitations=138 S. Ct. 1832; 201 [[L. Ed. 2d]] 200 |Prior=Certiorari to the United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit |Subsequent= |Holding=Lower court upheld by divided Court. |SCOTUS=2017 |PerCuriam=yes |NotParticipating=Kennedy |LawsApplied= }}
'''''Washington v. United States''''', 584 U.S. ___ (2018), was a [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]] case regarding Native American fishing rights in the U.S. state of [[Washington (state)|Washington]]. In the case, the court deadlocked 4-4, with Justice [[Anthony Kennedy]] recusing himself due to his prior involvement in the case as a judge on the [[United States Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals]].<ref>https://www.supremecourt.gov/DocketPDF/17/17-269/39869/20180323153617321_Recusal%20Letter%20in%20No.%2017-269.pdf</ref> The deadlock left standing a lower court ruling that the State of Washington must redesign and rebuild road culverts to allow salmon to swim upstream, to uphold Native American treaty rights to fish. The issue decided by the federal courts was whether, under the 1855–1856 [[Stevens Treaties (disambiguation)|Stevens Treaties]]<!--intentional link to DAB page-->, "the right to fish is the right to put a net in the water or the right for there to be fish to catch";<ref name=OPB/> however, with the 4-4 Supreme Court decision, it may not be binding on future court decisions.<ref name=NYT/>
The case was argued on April 18, 2018.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.scotusblog.com/case-files/cases/washington-v-united-states/ | title=Washington v. United States}}</ref><ref>https://www.supremecourt.gov/oral_arguments/argument_transcripts/2017/17-269_o75q.pdf</ref>
The cost of [[stream restoration]] demanded by the court decision was estimated to be $3.7 billion,<ref name=Kunkler2018/> making culvert replacement of the top [[List of Seattle megaprojects|megaprojects in the Seattle area]].
The decision was ''[[per curiam]]''.<ref>https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/17pdf/17-269_3eb4.pdf</ref>
==See also== *''[[United States v. Washington]]'' aka Boldt Decision, landmark 1974 Supreme Court ruling establishing treaty fishing rights in Washington *[[Puget Sound salmon]] *[[Stream restoration]]
